---
import ToolPage from '../../layouts/ToolPage.astro'
import Base64Island from '../../islands/Base64Island'
import { getToolMeta } from '@devkits/core'

const meta = getToolMeta('base64')!
---

<ToolPage meta={meta}>
  <Base64Island client:load />

  <section class="mt-12 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-4">How to Use</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>
        Type or paste your text into the input field, then click <strong>Encode</strong> to convert
        it to a Base64 string, or paste an existing Base64 string and click <strong>Decode</strong>
        to recover the original text. The tool handles standard Base64 as well as the URL-safe
        variant that replaces <code>+</code> and <code>/</code> with <code>-</code> and <code>_</code>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Typical developer use cases include encoding binary data for embedding in JSON payloads,
        creating <code>data:</code> URIs for small assets, passing credentials in HTTP Basic
        Authentication headers, and storing binary content in environments that only accept text
        such as environment variables or XML documents.
      </p>
      <p>
        Everything runs in your browser — no data is sent to any server. The tool also shows the
        exact byte size of both the input and the encoded output so you can see the size overhead
        at a glance.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Is Base64 a form of encryption?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          No. Base64 is an encoding scheme, not encryption. Anyone who has the Base64 string can
          decode it instantly without a key. Do not use Base64 to protect sensitive data — use
          proper encryption algorithms such as AES instead.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">How do I encode a UTF-8 string to Base64 in JavaScript?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Use <code>btoa(unescape(encodeURIComponent(str)))</code> for older environments, or the
          modern <code>TextEncoder</code> API: convert the string to bytes first, then encode those
          bytes. This tool handles multi-byte UTF-8 characters automatically.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">How much larger does a file get after Base64 encoding?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Base64-encoded data is approximately 33% larger than the original binary data because
          every 3 bytes of input are represented as 4 ASCII characters. Keep this overhead in mind
          when embedding images or other assets directly into HTML or JSON.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What is the difference between standard Base64 and URL-safe Base64?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Standard Base64 uses <code>+</code> and <code>/</code> characters which have special
          meaning in URLs. URL-safe Base64 replaces them with <code>-</code> and <code>_</code> so
          the encoded string can be used directly in query parameters and path segments without
          percent-encoding.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ToolPage>
